article.headline: Owls struggle, fall to 1-6

article.linkText: Temple falls to Illinois with Chaney watching at home
article.story: CHICAGO (AP) -- It took a defense he'd never seen and a case of nerves to finally trip up freshman Dee Brown. Only for a half, though. After a halftime pep talk from his coach and teammates, Brown scored 15 points to lead Illinois (No. 14 ESPN/USA Today, No. 15 AP) to a 70-54 win over roady-weary Temple on Saturday. The guard, playing in his hometown of Chicago, looked every bit like a first-year player in the opening half. He turned the ball over four times, missed all three of his shots and appeared lost against Temple's trademark matchup zone. In the second half, Brown could do no wrong. "I came out kind of nervous and flat. My teammates just told me, 'Come on. You've got to come out and play. No more nerves,''' Brown said. "That really helped me out.'' Temple (1-6) played its second straight game without coach John Chaney, who was at home while he recovers from pneumonia. Before the recent illness, the 70-year-old coach had missed just three games in 21 years at Temple. Brian Cook had 25 points and 11 rebounds as Illinois (7-0) held Temple to its worst shooting game of the season. The Illini had struggles of their own, mainly because of Temple's zone, which clogged the middle and slowed down an Illinois team that was averaging 84 points a game. "It felt like slow motion out there. But we kept our composure, and Dee really picked it up,'' Cook said. "He's a speed demon out there. We need that energy and he gets everybody going.'' Illinois was up 50-43 when Deron Williams and Sean Harrington made consecutive 3-pointers to key a late 20-9 run. With Chaney watching at home on television, the coach's trademark defense frustrated Illinois, which made a season-low 43 percent of its shots. But the Owls, playing in a school-record sixth straight road game, shot just 29 percent and made 6-of-28 3-point attempts. David Hawkins led Temple with 22 points, and senior Alex Wesby added 15. Temple's other three starters, all freshmen, combined for nine points on 3-of-13 shooting. Illinois built a 14-point lead in the first half behind near-perfect shooting from the free-throw line and poor outside shooting by Temple. The Illini made 13 of 14 free throws before the break. After making just one field goal in the first four minutes, Illinois went on a 19-3 run and later took a 28-14 lead when Harrington fired a long pass to freshman James Augustine for a dunk and the Illini's biggest edge of the half. Hawkins and Wesby combined to score 11 points during a 13-2 run for the Owls to get them within three at halftime. It was the closest Temple would get. Illinois opened up the second half with two straight baskets, the second coming on a steal and layup by Williams. Williams, one of three freshmen who started for Illinois, finished with eight points and seven assists. This was the first meeting between the teams since 1991. Illinois coach Bill Self said he wouldn't mind waiting at least that long before playing the Owls again. "It's tough to simulate what they do,'' Self said. "This is a game that nobody wants to play, but one that everyone needs to play.''
